# Agile Development Update

## Overview
This section documents the transition of the Computer Repair Management System into an Agile development approach. The system requirements and use cases from previous assignments were translated into user stories, a product backlog, and a sprint plan.

---

## User Stories
User stories were created using the Agile format:
"As a [role], I want [action] so that [benefit]."

These user stories were implemented and managed using GitHub Issues, allowing for traceability and task tracking throughout development.

---

## Product Backlog
All user stories were organized into a prioritized product backlog using the MoSCoW method:
- Must-have: Core system functionality required for operation
- Should-have: Important features but not critical for initial release
- Could-have: Optional features that enhance usability
- Won’t-have: Features deferred for future development

Story points were assigned to estimate effort and support sprint planning.

---

## Sprint Planning
A Sprint 1 plan was created to deliver a Minimum Viable Product (MVP). The sprint focuses on essential features such as device registration, intake recording, repair tracking, and status updates.

---

## GitHub Agile Tools
GitHub was used to manage Agile development:
- Issues: Represent user stories
- Milestones: Represent sprint planning (Sprint 1 – MVP)
- Project Board: Tracks progress using To Do, In Progress, and Done columns

This approach ensures transparency, organization, and alignment with Agile principles.
